{"title_page": "Ali Tayebnia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Ali Tayebnia\n|image       = Ali Tayebnia speaking at Conference of Monetary policy and Currency (cropped).jpg\n|caption     = \n|office      = [[Ministry of Economic Affairs and Finance (Iran)|Minister of Finance]]\n|president   = [[Hassan Rouhani]]\n|term_start  = 15 August 2013\n|term_end    = 20 August 2017\n|predecessor = [[Shamseddin Hosseini]]\n|successor   = [[Masoud Karbasian]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1960|4|5|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Isfahan]], [[Iran]]\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Independent politician|Independent]]\n|alma_mater  = [[University of Tehran]]\n|signature   = Ali Tayebnia signature.png\n|website     = [http://www.taiebnia.ir/ Personal website]\n|awards      = [[List of prizes, medals, and awards in Singapore|Lee Kuan Yew Prize]] (2017)<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.isna.ir/news/96051107183/%D8%B7%DB%8C%D8%A8-%D9%86%DB%8C%D8%A7-%D8%A8%D8%B1%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%87-%D8%AC%D8%A7%DB%8C%D8%B2%D9%87-%D8%A8%D9%86%DB%8C%D8%A7%D9%86%DA%AF%D8%B0%D8%A7%D8%B1-%D8%B3%D9%86%DA%AF%D8%A7%D9%BE%D9%88%D8%B1-%D9%86%D9%88%DB%8C%D9%86-%D8%B4%D8%AF|title=Tayebnia Won the Prize of Founding Father of Modern Singapore|date=2 August 2017|access-date=2 August 2017|work=ISNA|language=Persian|id=96051107183}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Ali Tayebnia''' ({{lang-fa|\u0639\u0644\u06cc \u0637\u06cc\u0628\u200c\u0646\u06cc\u0627}}, born 5 April 1960) is an [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] academic, economist and former Minister of Economic Affairs and Finance. He was designated by President [[Hassan Rouhani]] for the position on 4 August 2013 and was confirmed by the parliament on 15 August. He left the office on 20 August 2017.\n\n==Early life and education==\nTayebnia was born in [[Isfahan]] in 1960.<ref>{{cite web|last=Alfoneh|first=Ali|title=All the President's Men: Rouhani\u2019s Cabinet|url=http://www.defenddemocracy.org/media-hit/all-the-presidents-men-rouhanis-cabinet/|work=Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=13 August 2013|format=Policy Brief|date=5 August 2013}}</ref> He received his BA (1986) and MA (1989) in theoretical economics, and his PhD (1994) in economics, all from the [[University of Tehran]] and first in each class.<ref>[http://www.mefa.ir/Portal/Home/ShowPage.aspx?Object=Person&CategoryID=58ad17db-82be-4914-b88a-4eebc663cdd2&WebPartID=8aa938f7-dbbc-41df-90e0-73a78ec1be90&ID=27936cbd-29fd-455a-ae85-53e0b994aca6 Ministry Profile]</ref><ref name=jm8>{{cite news|last=Memarian|first=Jahandad|title=New Iranian Cabinet Nominees: Building Bridges Between Factions to Yield Reform|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jahandad-memarian/new-iranian-cabinet-nomin_b_3726826.html|accessdate=11 August 2013|work=The Huffington Post|date=8 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rouhani's proposed cabinet line-up|url=http://www.iran-daily.com/1392/5/15/MainPaper/4601/Page/3/Index.htm#|accessdate=16 August 2013|newspaper=Iran Daily|date=6 August 2013}}</ref> As part of Tayebnia's doctoral studies, he spent a year studying at the [[London School of Economics]] under the supervision of Laurence Harris.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0637\u06cc\u0628\u200c\u0646\u06cc\u0627\u060c\u200c \u0628\u0647 \u0648\u0632\u0631\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0642\u062a\u0635\u0627\u062f \u0631\u0633\u06cc\u062f|url=http://www.isna.ir/fa/news/92052413727/%D8%B7%DB%8C%D8%A8-%D9%86%DB%8C%D8%A7-%D8%A8%D9%87-%D9%88%D8%B2%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%B1%D8%B3%DB%8C%D8%AF|accessdate=1 March 2014|work=ISNA|date=17 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=LSE in print|url=http://www.lse.ac.uk/intranet/news/informationForStaff/staffStudentsAndAlumni/dailyHeadlines/2013/September/06September2013.aspx|accessdate=1 March 2014|work=The London School of Economics and Political Science|date=6 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Ali Tayebnia meeting German Vice Chancellor Sigmar Gabriel in Tehran 139507121551065348833554.jpg|thumb|left|Tayebnia and German [[Vice Chancellor of Germany|Vice Chancellor]] and Economic Minister [[Sigmar Gabriel]] in [[Tehran]], 3 October 2016]]\nTayenia is an academic and has served in various state institutions regarding economy and finance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Possible nominees for Rohani's cabinet|url=http://www.gulfinthemedia.com/index.php?m=&id=658933&lang=en|accessdate=11 August 2013|work=Gulf in the Media|date=1 August 2013|agency=Tehran Times}}</ref> He was a faculty member at his alma mater, the University of Tehran.<ref name=jm8/><ref>{{cite web|title=President Hassan Rouhani's pragmatic conservative, security-intelligence-oriented Cabinet nominations|url=http://www.iranpolitik.com/2013/08/06/analysis/president-hassan-rouhanis-cabinet/|work=Iran Politik|accessdate=13 August 2013|date=6 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130818094857/http://www.iranpolitik.com/2013/08/06/analysis/president-hassan-rouhanis-cabinet/|archive-date=18 August 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> His field of interest is public economics<ref name=ft/>\n\nHe was the secretary of the economic commission from 1997 to 2000.<ref name=irna>{{cite news|title=Biography of Tayebnia, proposed as minister of Economic Affairs and Finance|url=http://www3.kermanshah.irna.ir/en/News/80763598/Politic/Biography_of_Tayebnia,_proposed_as_minister_of_Economic_Affairs_and_Finance|accessdate=11 August 2013|work=IRNA|date=5 August 2013|location=Tehran|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304080144/http://www3.kermanshah.irna.ir/en/News/80763598/Politic/Biography_of_Tayebnia,_proposed_as_minister_of_Economic_Affairs_and_Finance|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> He served as the deputy head of the Presidential Office for planning under the former President [[Mohammad Khatami]] from 2001 to 2005.<ref name=irna/> Then he was again named the secretary of the economic commission in 2005 and his tenure lasted until 2007.<ref name=irna/>\n\nHe was a representative of and an advisor to [[Mohammad Reza Aref]] during [[2013 Iranian presidential election|the 2013 presidential elections]].<ref name=jm8/> He was also Aref's economic advisor.<ref>{{cite news|author=Mustafa al Labbad|title=Rouhani's Cabinet Seeks New Balance in Iranian Policies|url=http://assafir.com/MulhakArticle.aspx?EditionId=2539&MulhakArticleId=1787820&MulhakId=6367#.Ug3dQ2TAVgs|accessdate=16 August 2013|newspaper=As Safir|date=15 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Iran politics: Rowhani takes a centre line in his cabinet nominees|url=http://viewswire.eiu.com/index.asp?layout=VWArticleVW3&article_id=1670821351&refm=vwHome&page_title=Latest%20analysis|accessdate=29 August 2013|work=ViewsWire|date=8 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 August 2013, he was proposed by President [[Hassan Rouhani]] as minister of economic affairs and finance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran president unveils proposed Cabinet list|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail/2013/08/04/317160/iran-president-unveils-proposed-cabinet/|accessdate=11 August 2013|work=PressTV|date=4 August 2013|agency=ILNA}}</ref> On 15 August, the Majlis approved him as minister, giving 274 votes for and 7 votes against.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iranian Parliament Gives Vote of Confidence to Majority of Rouhani's Proposed Ministers|url=http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.aspx?nn=13920524000980|accessdate=15 August 2013|work=Fars News|date=15 August 2013}}</ref> He was given the highest votes for with the rate of 96.5% which was also all-time record for Iranian confirmation process.<ref>{{cite news|title=96.5 percent voting for a minister \u2013 all time record for Islamic Republic of Iran|url=http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/154231/96-5-percent-voting-for-a-minister-all-time-record-for-islamic-republic-of-iran.html|accessdate=22 August 2013|work=The Journal of Turkish Weekly|date=16 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018233237/http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/154231/96-5-percent-voting-for-a-minister-all-time-record-for-islamic-republic-of-iran.html|archive-date=18 October 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Views===\n''[[Financial Times]]'' described Tayebnia as a [[Iranian Reformists|reform]]-minded academic in August 2013.<ref name=ft>{{cite news|last=Khalaj|first=Monavar|title=Iran parliament approves new president's cabinet nominees|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/834e932c-05d4-11e3-ad01-00144feab7de.html#axzz2c250dfme|accessdate=15 August 2013|newspaper=Financial Times|date=15 August 2013|location=Tehran}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Economy of Iran]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Ali Tayebnia}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Shamseddin Hosseini]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Economic Affairs and Finance (Iran)|Minister of Economic Affairs and Finance]]|years=2013\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Masoud Karbasian]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Rouhani cabinet}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tayebnia, Ali}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Iranian academics]]\n[[Category:Iranian economists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Isfahan]]\n[[Category:University of Tehran alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Tehran faculty]]\n[[Category:Finance ministers of Iran]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Ali Tayebnia\n|image       = Ali Tayebnia speaking at Conference of Monetary policy and Currency (cropped).jpg\n|caption     = \n|office      = [[Ministry of Economic Affairs and Finance (Iran)|Minister of Finance]]\n|president   = [[Hassan Rouhani]]\n|term_start  = 15 August 2013\n|term_end    = 20 August 2017\n|predecessor = [[Shamseddin Hosseini]]\n|successor   = [[Masoud Karbasian]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1960|4|5|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Isfahan]], [[Iran]]\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Independent politician|Independent]]\n|alma_mater  = [[University of Tehran]]\n|signature   = Ali Tayebnia signature.png\n|website     = [http://www.taiebnia.ir/ Personal website]\n|awards      = [[List of prizes, medals, and awards in Singapore|Lee Kuan Yew Prize]] (2017)<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.isna.ir/news/96051107183/%D8%B7%DB%8C%D8%A8-%D9%86%DB%8C%D8%A7-%D8%A8%D8%B1%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%87-%D8%AC%D8%A7%DB%8C%D8%B2%D9%87-%D8%A8%D9%86%DB%8C%D8%A7%D9%86%DA%AF%D8%B0%D8%A7%D8%B1-%D8%B3%D9%86%DA%AF%D8%A7%D9%BE%D9%88%D8%B1-%D9%86%D9%88%DB%8C%D9%86-%D8%B4%D8%AF|title=Tayebnia Won the Prize of Founding Father of Modern Singapore|date=2 August 2017|access-date=2 August 2017|work=ISNA|language=Persian|id=96051107183}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Ali Tayebnia''' ({{lang-fa|\u0639\u0644\u06cc \u0637\u06cc\u0628\u200c\u0646\u06cc\u0627}}, born 5 April 1960) is an [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] academic, economist and former Minister of Economic Affairs and Finance. He was designated by President [[Hassan Rouhani]] for the position on 4 August 2013 and was confirmed by the parliament on 15 August. He left the office on 20 August 2017.\n\n==Early life and education==\nTayebnia was born in [[Isfahan]] in 1960.<ref>{{cite web|last=Alfoneh|first=Ali|title=All the President's Men: Rouhani\u2019s Cabinet|url=http://www.defenddemocracy.org/media-hit/all-the-presidents-men-rouhanis-cabinet/|work=Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=13 August 2013|format=Policy Brief|date=5 August 2013}}</ref> He received his BA (1986) and MA (1989) in theoretical economics, and his PhD (1994) in economics, all from the [[University of Tehran]] and first in each class.<ref>[http://www.mefa.ir/Portal/Home/ShowPage.aspx?Object=Person&CategoryID=58ad17db-82be-4914-b88a-4eebc663cdd2&WebPartID=8aa938f7-dbbc-41df-90e0-73a78ec1be90&ID=27936cbd-29fd-455a-ae85-53e0b994aca6 Ministry Profile]</ref><ref name=jm8>{{cite news|last=Memarian|first=Jahandad|title=New Iranian Cabinet Nominees: Building Bridges Between Factions to Yield Reform|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jahandad-memarian/new-iranian-cabinet-nomin_b_3726826.html|accessdate=11 August 2013|work=The Huffington Post|date=8 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rouhani's proposed cabinet line-up|url=http://www.iran-daily.com/1392/5/15/MainPaper/4601/Page/3/Index.htm#|accessdate=16 August 2013|newspaper=Iran Daily|date=6 August 2013}}</ref> As part of Tayebnia's doctoral studies, he spent a year studying at the [[London School of Economics]] under the supervision of Laurence Harris.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0637\u06cc\u0628\u200c\u0646\u06cc\u0627\u060c\u200c \u0628\u0647 \u0648\u0632\u0631\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0642\u062a\u0635\u0627\u062f \u0631\u0633\u06cc\u062f|url=http://www.isna.ir/fa/news/92052413727/%D8%B7%DB%8C%D8%A8-%D9%86%DB%8C%D8%A7-%D8%A8%D9%87-%D9%88%D8%B2%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%B1%D8%B3%DB%8C%D8%AF|accessdate=1 March 2014|work=ISNA|date=17 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=LSE in print|url=http://www.lse.ac.uk/intranet/news/informationForStaff/staffStudentsAndAlumni/dailyHeadlines/2013/September/06September2013.aspx|accessdate=1 March 2014|work=The London School of Economics and Political Science|date=6 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Ali Tayebnia meeting German Vice Chancellor Sigmar Gabriel in Tehran 139507121551065348833554.jpg|thumb|left|Tayebnia and German [[Vice Chancellor of Germany|Vice Chancellor]] and Economic Minister [[Sigmar Gabriel]] in [[Tehran]], 3 October 2016]]\nTayenia is an academic and has served in various state institutions regarding economy and finance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Possible nominees for Rohani's cabinet|url=http://www.gulfinthemedia.com/index.php?m=&id=658933&lang=en|accessdate=11 August 2013|work=Gulf in the Media|date=1 August 2013|agency=Tehran Times}}</ref> He was a faculty member at his alma mater, the University of Tehran.<ref name=jm8/><ref>{{cite web|title=President Hassan Rouhani's pragmatic conservative, security-intelligence-oriented Cabinet nominations|url=http://www.iranpolitik.com/2013/08/06/analysis/president-hassan-rouhanis-cabinet/|work=Iran Politik|accessdate=13 August 2013|date=6 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130818094857/http://www.iranpolitik.com/2013/08/06/analysis/president-hassan-rouhanis-cabinet/|archive-date=18 August 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> His field of interest is public economics<ref name=ft/>\n\nHe was the secretary of the economic commission from 1997 to 2000.<ref name=irna>{{cite news|title=Biography of Tayebnia, proposed as minister of Economic Affairs and Finance|url=http://www3.kermanshah.irna.ir/en/News/80763598/Politic/Biography_of_Tayebnia,_proposed_as_minister_of_Economic_Affairs_and_Finance|accessdate=11 August 2013|work=IRNA|date=5 August 2013|location=Tehran|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304080144/http://www3.kermanshah.irna.ir/en/News/80763598/Politic/Biography_of_Tayebnia,_proposed_as_minister_of_Economic_Affairs_and_Finance|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> He served as the deputy head of the Presidential Office for planning under the former President [[Mohammad Khatami]] from 2001 to 2005.<ref name=irna/> Then he was again named the secretary of the economic commission in 2005 and his tenure lasted until 2007.<ref name=irna/>\n\nHe was a representative of and an advisor to [[Mohammad Reza Aref]] during [[2013 Iranian presidential election|the 2013 presidential elections]].<ref name=jm8/> He was also Aref's economic advisor.<ref>{{cite news|author=Mustafa al Labbad|title=Rouhani's Cabinet Seeks New Balance in Iranian Policies|url=http://assafir.com/MulhakArticle.aspx?EditionId=2539&MulhakArticleId=1787820&MulhakId=6367#.Ug3dQ2TAVgs|accessdate=16 August 2013|newspaper=As Safir|date=15 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Iran politics: Rowhani takes a centre line in his cabinet nominees|url=http://viewswire.eiu.com/index.asp?layout=VWArticleVW3&article_id=1670821351&refm=vwHome&page_title=Latest%20analysis|accessdate=29 August 2013|work=ViewsWire|date=8 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 August 2013, he was proposed by President [[Hassan Rouhani]] as minister of economic affairs and finance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran president unveils proposed Cabinet list|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail/2013/08/04/317160/iran-president-unveils-proposed-cabinet/|accessdate=11 August 2013|work=PressTV|date=4 August 2013|agency=ILNA}}</ref> On 15 August, the Majlis approved him as minister, giving 274 votes for and 7 votes against.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iranian Parliament Gives Vote of Confidence to Majority of Rouhani's Proposed Ministers|url=http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.aspx?nn=13920524000980|accessdate=15 August 2013|work=Fars News|date=15 August 2013}}</ref> He was given the highest votes for with the rate of 96.5% which was also all-time record for Iranian confirmation process.<ref>{{cite news|title=96.5 percent voting for a minister \u2013 all time record for Islamic Republic of Iran|url=http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/154231/96-5-percent-voting-for-a-minister-all-time-record-for-islamic-republic-of-iran.html|accessdate=22 August 2013|work=The Journal of Turkish Weekly|date=16 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018233237/http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/154231/96-5-percent-voting-for-a-minister-all-time-record-for-islamic-republic-of-iran.html|archive-date=18 October 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Views===\n''[[Financial Times]]'' described Tayebnia as a [[Iranian Reformists|reform]]-minded academic in August 2013.<ref name=ft>{{cite news|last=Khalaj|first=Monavar|title=Iran parliament approves new president's cabinet nominees|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/834e932c-05d4-11e3-ad01-00144feab7de.html#axzz2c250dfme|accessdate=15 August 2013|newspaper=Financial Times|date=15 August 2013|location=Tehran}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Economy of Iran]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Ali Tayebnia}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Shamseddin Hosseini]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Economic Affairs and Finance (Iran)|Minister of Economic Affairs and Finance]]|years=2013\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Masoud Karbasian]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Rouhani cabinet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tayebnia, Ali}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Iranian academics]]\n[[Category:Iranian economists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Isfahan]]\n[[Category:University of Tehran alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Tehran faculty]]\n[[Category:Finance ministers of Iran]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ali_Tayebnia"}
{"title_page": "Ali Sharif Al Emadi", "text_new": "{{short description|Qatari economist and businessman|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = H.E Ali Sharif Al Emadi\n| image               = \n| imagesize           = \n| office              = Minister of Finance\n| monarch             = [[Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani]]\n| primeminister       = [[Abdullah bin Nasser bin Khalifa Al Thani|Abdullah bin Nasser Al Thani]]\n| predecessor         = [[Yousef Hussain Kamal Al Emadi]]\n| successor           = \n| term_start          = 26 June 2013\n| term_end            = \n| birth_date          = \n| birth_place         = \n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| restingplace        = \n| party               = \n| residence           = \n| alma_mater          = [[University of Arizona]]\n| spouse              = \n| nationality         = Qatari\n| religion            = \n| children            = \n| website             = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Ali Sharif Al Emadi''' is a Qatari economist and businessman. He has been serving as the [[Finance minister|minister of finance]] since June 2013. He also serves as chairman of the [[QNB Group]] and is on the board of directors of [[Ooredoo]], Tunisian-Qatari Bank, and [[Union of Arab Banks]].<ref name=coun>{{cite web|url=http://www.cm.gov.qa/English/councilofministers/Pages/Al-Emadi.aspx|title=HE Mr. Ali Shareef Al Emadi , Minister of Finance|work=General Secrretariat of the Council of Ministers|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"top100\">{{cite web|url=http://gulfbusiness.com/lists/top-100-arab-power-list-2013/ali-shareef-al-emadi/#.VN938_nF95Y|title=Top 100 Powerful Arabs 2013|work=Gulf Business|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nAl Emadi holds a bachelor's degree in finance from [[the University of Arizona]].<ref name=coun/><ref name=gnews/>\n\n==Career==\nAl Emadi worked in the banking control department of [[Qatar Central Bank|the Qatar Central Bank]] for eight years until 1998.<ref name=gnews/><ref name=gsn/> He joined [[Qatar National Bank]] in 1998.<ref name=gsn/> He was appointed the bank's chief executive in 2005, succeeding Saeed bin Abdullah Al Misnad in the post.<ref name=gsn/> Emadi was included in the ''Top 100 Powerful Arabs'' list in February 2013, coming in 32nd place due to his role in the rapid growth and expansion of the Qatar National Bank.<ref name=\"top100\"/> His tenure lasted until June 2013.<ref name=gnews>{{cite news|title=Chief who built the biggest Arab bank takes over Qatar finances|url=http://www.gulf-times.com/business/191/details/358010/chief-who-built-the-biggest-arab-bank-takes-over-qatar-finances|accessdate=17 August 2013|newspaper=Gulf News|date=1 July 2013|agency=Bloomberg|location=Doha}}</ref> He was appointed minister of economy and finance on 26 June in a cabinet reshuffle following the ascension of Sheikh [[Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani]] as [[Emir of Qatar]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Simeon Kerr|title=Qatar\u2019s new emir replaces prime minister|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/193af872-de2e-11e2-9b47-00144feab7de.html#axzz2cCwoPntG|accessdate=17 August 2013|newspaper=Financial Times|date=26 June 2013|location=Doha}}</ref> Emadi replaced [[Yousef Hussain Kamal]] in the post.<ref name=gsn>{{cite journal|title=Qatar\u2019s new finance minister:Ali Sherif Al-Emadi|journal=Gulf States Newsletter (GSN)|date=4 July 2013|issue=950|url=http://the-mea.co.uk/sites/default/files/GSN_950_MEA_Jul13.pdf|accessdate=17 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017171719/http://the-mea.co.uk/sites/default/files/GSN_950_MEA_Jul13.pdf|archive-date=17 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe was announced as a member of the administrative council of [[Qatar Investment Authority|the Qatar Investment Authority]] (QIA) on 1 July 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qatar's former PM loses role at wealth fund|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/qatar-s-former-pm-loses-role-at-wealth-fund-507613.html#.Ug8k_GTAVgs|accessdate=17 August 2013|work=Arabian Business|date=3 July 2013|agency=Reuters}}</ref> He was also made board chairman of Qatar National Bank on 7 July 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qatar's QNB names finance minister Emadi as board chairman|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/07/07/qatar-qnb-chairman-idUSL6N0FD0AT20130707|accessdate=17 August 2013|work=Reuters|date=7 July 2013|location=Dubai}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Intercept]]'' reported on 2 March 2018 that [[Jared Kushner]] and his felon father, [[Charles Kushner]], made a proposal to Qatar\u2019s finance minister, Ali Sharif Al Emadi, in April 2017 to secure investment into 666 5th Avenue asset in his family's company\u2019s portfolio. When his request was not fulfilled, a group of Middle Eastern countries, with Jared Kushner\u2019s backing, initiated a diplomatic assault that culminated in a [[Qatar\u2013Saudi Arabia proxy conflict|blockade of Qatar]]. Kushner specifically undermined the efforts by [[Secretary of state (U.S. state government)|Secretary of State]] [[Rex Tillerson]]<nowiki/>to bring an end to the standoff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2018/03/02/jared-kushner-real-estate-qatar-blockade/|title=Jared Kushner\u2019s Real-Estate Firm Sought Money Directly From Qatar Government Weeks Before Blockade|author1=Clayton Swisher|author2=Ryan Grim|date=2 March 2018|work=The Intercept|language=en-US|access-date=3 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Emadi, Ali Sharif Al}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Qatar]]\n[[Category:Qatari economists]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Qatari economist and businessman|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Minister\n| name                = H.E Ali Sharif Al Emadi\n| image               = \n| imagesize           = \n| office              = Minister of Finance\n| monarch             = [[Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani]]\n| primeminister       = [[Abdullah bin Nasser bin Khalifa Al Thani|Abdullah bin Nasser Al Thani]]\n| predecessor         = [[Yousef Hussain Kamal Al Emadi]]\n| successor           = \n| term_start          = 26 June 2013\n| term_end            = \n| birth_date          = \n| birth_place         = \n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| restingplace        = \n| party               = \n| residence           = \n| alma_mater          = [[University of Arizona]]\n| spouse              = \n| nationality         = Qatari\n| religion            = \n| children            = \n| website             = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Ali Sharif Al Emadi''' is a Qatari economist and businessman. He has been serving as the [[Finance minister|minister of finance]] since June 2013. He also serves as chairman of the [[QNB Group]] and is on the board of directors of [[Ooredoo]], Tunisian-Qatari Bank, and [[Union of Arab Banks]].<ref name=coun>{{cite web|url=http://www.cm.gov.qa/English/councilofministers/Pages/Al-Emadi.aspx|title=HE Mr. Ali Shareef Al Emadi , Minister of Finance|work=General Secrretariat of the Council of Ministers|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"top100\">{{cite web|url=http://gulfbusiness.com/lists/top-100-arab-power-list-2013/ali-shareef-al-emadi/#.VN938_nF95Y|title=Top 100 Powerful Arabs 2013|work=Gulf Business|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nAl Emadi holds a bachelor's degree in finance from [[the University of Arizona]].<ref name=coun/><ref name=gnews/>\n\n==Career==\nAl Emadi worked in the banking control department of [[Qatar Central Bank|the Qatar Central Bank]] for eight years until 1998.<ref name=gnews/><ref name=gsn/> He joined [[Qatar National Bank]] in 1998.<ref name=gsn/> He was appointed the bank's chief executive in 2005, succeeding Saeed bin Abdullah Al Misnad in the post.<ref name=gsn/> Emadi was included in the ''Top 100 Powerful Arabs'' list in February 2013, coming in 32nd place due to his role in the rapid growth and expansion of the Qatar National Bank.<ref name=\"top100\"/> His tenure lasted until June 2013.<ref name=gnews>{{cite news|title=Chief who built the biggest Arab bank takes over Qatar finances|url=http://www.gulf-times.com/business/191/details/358010/chief-who-built-the-biggest-arab-bank-takes-over-qatar-finances|accessdate=17 August 2013|newspaper=Gulf News|date=1 July 2013|agency=Bloomberg|location=Doha}}</ref> He was appointed minister of economy and finance on 26 June in a cabinet reshuffle following the ascension of Sheikh [[Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani]] as [[Emir of Qatar]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Simeon Kerr|title=Qatar\u2019s new emir replaces prime minister|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/193af872-de2e-11e2-9b47-00144feab7de.html#axzz2cCwoPntG|accessdate=17 August 2013|newspaper=Financial Times|date=26 June 2013|location=Doha}}</ref> Emadi replaced [[Yousef Hussain Kamal]] in the post.<ref name=gsn>{{cite journal|title=Qatar\u2019s new finance minister:Ali Sherif Al-Emadi|journal=Gulf States Newsletter (GSN)|date=4 July 2013|issue=950|url=http://the-mea.co.uk/sites/default/files/GSN_950_MEA_Jul13.pdf|accessdate=17 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017171719/http://the-mea.co.uk/sites/default/files/GSN_950_MEA_Jul13.pdf|archive-date=17 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe was announced as a member of the administrative council of [[Qatar Investment Authority|the Qatar Investment Authority]] (QIA) on 1 July 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qatar's former PM loses role at wealth fund|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/qatar-s-former-pm-loses-role-at-wealth-fund-507613.html#.Ug8k_GTAVgs|accessdate=17 August 2013|work=Arabian Business|date=3 July 2013|agency=Reuters}}</ref> He was also made board chairman of Qatar National Bank on 7 July 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qatar's QNB names finance minister Emadi as board chairman|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/07/07/qatar-qnb-chairman-idUSL6N0FD0AT20130707|accessdate=17 August 2013|work=Reuters|date=7 July 2013|location=Dubai}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Intercept]]'' reported on 2 March 2018 that [[Jared Kushner]] and his felon father, [[Charles Kushner]], made a proposal to Qatar\u2019s finance minister, Ali Sharif Al Emadi, in April 2017 to secure investment into 666 5th Avenue asset in his family's company\u2019s portfolio. When his request was not fulfilled, a group of Middle Eastern countries, with Jared Kushner\u2019s backing, initiated a diplomatic assault that culminated in a [[Qatar\u2013Saudi Arabia proxy conflict|blockade of Qatar]]. Kushner specifically undermined the efforts by [[Secretary of state (U.S. state government)|Secretary of State]] [[Rex Tillerson]]<nowiki/>to bring an end to the standoff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2018/03/02/jared-kushner-real-estate-qatar-blockade/|title=Jared Kushner\u2019s Real-Estate Firm Sought Money Directly From Qatar Government Weeks Before Blockade|author1=Clayton Swisher|author2=Ryan Grim|date=2 March 2018|work=The Intercept|language=en-US|access-date=3 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Emadi, Ali Sharif Al}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Qatar]]\n[[Category:Qatari economists]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ali_Sharif_Al_Emadi"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saint Kitts and Nevis", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in the Saint Kitts and Nevis}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saint Kitts and Nevis\n| map1 = \n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Saint Kitts and Nevis]]\n| first_case = \n| arrival_date = 25 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=25|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[China]]\n| recovery_cases = 0\n| deaths = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 11<ref name=first >{{Cite web |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/st-kitts-and-nevis-confirms-two-covid-19-cases/ |title=St Kitts and Nevis confirms two COVID-19 cases |date=25 March 2020 |work=St. Lucia Times}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Saint Kitts and Nevis]] in March 2020.\n__TOC__\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, who had initially come to the attention of the WHO on 31 December 2019. This cluster was initially linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in Wuhan City. However, some of those first cases with laboratory confirmed results had no link to the market, and the source of the epidemic is unknown.<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center|last=Elsevier|date=|website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds4March2020\">{{Cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Matt|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic?|date=4 March 2020|work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|issn=1357-0978}}</ref>\n\nUnlike [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]], the [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 <ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus|website=Imperial News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> has been much lower, but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=\"WFSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" /> COVID-19 typically appears with about seven days of [[Influenza-like illness|flu-like symptoms]] followed by some people progressing to symptoms of a [[viral pneumonia]] requiring admission to hospital.<ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" /> From 19 March, COVID-19 was no longer classified as a \"High consequence infectious disease\".<ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\" />\n\n==Timeline==\n\n=== March 2020 ===\nOn March 25, a 21-year-old male and a 57-year-old female that arrived in the Federation from [[New York City]] became the first two confirmed cases of [[COVID-19]]. Both are nationals of St Kitts and Nevis.<ref name=first/>\n\nOn Saturday, March 28, 2020, St Kitts and Nevis recorded five additional cases of COVID-19 bringing the total number of confirmed cases to seven (7). \"These cases involved three females and two males who are all citizens of St Kitts and Nevis. The females were aged 10 months, 24 years and 36 years, while the two male patients were 29 years and 39 years,\u201d Minister of State with responsibility for Health, Sen. the Hon Wendy Phipps said in a statement. She said all five of these cases are travel related \u201cmeaning that the cases were imported into the Federation\u201d. \u201cThis determination was made based on the patients\u2019 travel history to St Maarten and Antigua during the period March 6 to 13, 2020,\u201d the junior health minister said.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/st-kitts-nevis-reports-five-more-coronavirus-cases-now-seven/ |title = St Kitts-Nevis reports five more coronavirus cases, now seven|date = 30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn Sunday March 29, 2020 \u201cSt Kitts and Nevis recorded one additional case of COVID-19 bringing the total number of confirmed cases to eight (8). The Minister of State with responsibility for Health, Sen. the Hon Wendy Phipps disclosed that \"The patient is a 51-year-old female who is citizen of St Kitts and Nevis and resident on Nevis\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/st-kitts-and-nevis-covid-19-cases-quadruple-in-six-days/ | title=St Kitts and Nevis' COVID-19 cases quadruple in six days| date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\n(date unverified). 9th case. St Kitts and Nevis recorded one additional case of COVID-19 and brought the total number confirmed cases to nine (9). The patient was a citizen of St Kitts and Nevis and resident on Nevis,\u201d Sen Phipps informed the nation at a 3:p,m. update.(2nd on Nevis) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sknvibes.com/news/newsdetails.cfm/112176|title=SKNVibes {{!}} Community transmission of Coronavirus reported on Nevis|website=www.sknvibes.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nOn Saturday, April 4, 2020 \"St. Kitts and Nevis recorded one (1) additional case of COVID-19. Junior Minister of Health, Senator Wendy Phipps announced it brought the total number of confirmed cases to 10. The patient was a 66 year-old female who is a citizen of St. Kitts and Nevis, and resident on Nevis. \u201c <ref>http://thelabourspokesman.com/coronavirus-st-kitts-nevis-case-10-66-year-old-tests-positive/</ref>\n\nOn Monday, April 6th, 2020\"  The Federal Ministry of Health in St. Kitts and Nevis confirmed today that as at 12:29 p.m. on Monday, April 06, 2020, there has been an additional confirmed case of COVID-19. This raises the total number of positive results to eleven. The newest case is a 35-year-old male citizen of the twin-island federation residing in Nevis. This confirmation means that there are now four cases of the coronavirus on Nevis and seven on St. Kitts. <ref>https://zizonline.com/st-kitts-nevis-government-announces-additional-covid-19-case-all-patients-in-reasonably-well-condition/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Saint Kitts and Nevis|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Saint Kitts and Nevis]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Caribbean|Saint Kitts and Nevis]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Saint Kitts and Nevis]]\n\n\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n{{SaintKittsNevis-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in the Saint Kitts and Nevis}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saint Kitts and Nevis\n| map1 = \n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Saint Kitts and Nevis]]\n| first_case = \n| arrival_date = 25 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=25|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[China]]\n| recovery_cases = 0\n| deaths = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 11<ref name=first >{{Cite web |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/st-kitts-and-nevis-confirms-two-covid-19-cases/ |title=St Kitts and Nevis confirms two COVID-19 cases |date=25 March 2020 |work=St. Lucia Times}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Saint Kitts and Nevis]] in March 2020.\n__TOC__\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, who had initially come to the attention of the WHO on 31 December 2019. This cluster was initially linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in Wuhan City. However, some of those first cases with laboratory confirmed results had no link to the market, and the source of the epidemic is unknown.<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center|last=Elsevier|date=|website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds4March2020\">{{Cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Matt|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic?|date=4 March 2020|work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|issn=1357-0978}}</ref>\n\nUnlike [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]], the [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 <ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus|website=Imperial News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> has been much lower, but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=\"WFSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" /> COVID-19 typically appears with about seven days of [[Influenza-like illness|flu-like symptoms]] followed by some people progressing to symptoms of a [[viral pneumonia]] requiring admission to hospital.<ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" /> From 19 March, COVID-19 was no longer classified as a \"High consequence infectious disease\".<ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\" />\n\n==Timeline==\n\n=== March 2020 ===\nOn March 25, a 21-year-old male and a 57-year-old female that arrived in the Federation from [[New York City]] became the first two confirmed cases of [[COVID-19]]. Both are nationals of St Kitts and Nevis.<ref name=first/>\n\nOn Saturday, March 28, 2020, St Kitts and Nevis recorded five additional cases of COVID-19 bringing the total number of confirmed cases to seven (7). \"These cases involved three females and two males who are all citizens of St Kitts and Nevis. The females were aged 10 months, 24 years and 36 years, while the two male patients were 29 years and 39 years,\u201d Minister of State with responsibility for Health, Sen. the Hon Wendy Phipps said in a statement. She said all five of these cases are travel related \u201cmeaning that the cases were imported into the Federation\u201d. \u201cThis determination was made based on the patients\u2019 travel history to St Maarten and Antigua during the period March 6 to 13, 2020,\u201d the junior health minister said.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/st-kitts-nevis-reports-five-more-coronavirus-cases-now-seven/ |title = St Kitts-Nevis reports five more coronavirus cases, now seven|date = 30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn Sunday March 29, 2020 \u201cSt Kitts and Nevis recorded one additional case of COVID-19 bringing the total number of confirmed cases to eight (8). The Minister of State with responsibility for Health, Sen. the Hon Wendy Phipps disclosed that \"The patient is a 51-year-old female who is citizen of St Kitts and Nevis and resident on Nevis\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/st-kitts-and-nevis-covid-19-cases-quadruple-in-six-days/ | title=St Kitts and Nevis' COVID-19 cases quadruple in six days| date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\n(date unverified). 9th case. St Kitts and Nevis recorded one additional case of COVID-19 and brought the total number confirmed cases to nine (9). The patient was a citizen of St Kitts and Nevis and resident on Nevis,\u201d Sen Phipps informed the nation at a 3:p,m. update.(2nd on Nevis) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sknvibes.com/news/newsdetails.cfm/112176|title=SKNVibes {{!}} Community transmission of Coronavirus reported on Nevis|website=www.sknvibes.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nOn Saturday, April 4, 2020 \"St. Kitts and Nevis recorded one (1) additional case of COVID-19. Junior Minister of Health, Senator Wendy Phipps announced it brought the total number of confirmed cases to 10. The patient was a 66 year-old female who is a citizen of St. Kitts and Nevis, and resident on Nevis. \u201c <ref>http://thelabourspokesman.com/coronavirus-st-kitts-nevis-case-10-66-year-old-tests-positive/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Saint Kitts and Nevis|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Saint Kitts and Nevis]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Caribbean|Saint Kitts and Nevis]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Saint Kitts and Nevis]]\n\n\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n{{SaintKittsNevis-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nevisdatanerd", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril 2020", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Saint_Kitts_and_Nevis"}
{"title_page": "DIL (musician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Mr DiL\n| background      = solo_singer\n| image           = DiL pic.jpg\n| caption         = DiL during a photoshoot\n| birth_name      = Dil Anthony Chike Ajufo\n| birth_place     = [[Westminster]], London, UK.\n| genre           = [[R&B]], Pop, [[Afro pop music|Afropop]], [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| occupation      = Musician<br />songwriter<br />[[sound engineer]]<br />producer\n| years_active    = 2005\u2013present\n| label           = Trakk Records<br />[[Red Rhythm]]\n| associated_acts = [[Iyanya]]<br />[[Yemi Alade]]<br />[[Lynxxx]]<br />[[Praiz]] \n| website         = {{URL|www.trakkrecords.com}}\n}}\n'''Dil Anthony Ajufo aka DiL or Mr DiL''' is a [[British Nigerian|British-Nigerian]] singer and producer.<ref>{{cite web|title=UK returnee, DIL on why he relocated to Nigeria|url=http://encomium.ng/uk-returnee-dil-on-why-he-relocated-to-nigeria/|publisher=Encomium|accessdate=12 August 2015|date=21 March 2014}}</ref> He is best known for his 2015 song \"Pretty Girls\"<ref name=\"Pretty Girls\">{{cite web |url = http://lindaikeji.blogspot.com/2014/12/new-video-dil-feat-iyanya-pretty-girls.html |title = New Video: DIL feat Iyanya \u2013 Pretty Girls |publisher = [[Linda Ikeji]] |date = 13 December 2014|accessdate = 30 July 2015 }}</ref> featuring [[Iyanya]]. He is also known for his collaboration with [[Yemi Alade]] on the popular song \"Temperature\".<ref name=\"Temperature\">{{cite web |url = http://www.bellanaija.com/2015/03/13/new-video-yemi-alade-featuring-dil-temperature/ |title = New Video: Yemi Alade featuring Dil \u2013 Temperature |publisher = [[BellaNaija]] |date = 13 March 2015|accessdate = 30 July 2015 }}</ref> On his debut single \"Acapella\" he collaborated with [[Lynxxx]] and Praiz. He was signed with Red Rhythm<ref name=\"Red Rhythm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bucksmusicgroup.com/composers/Red_Rhythm_Simon_Britton_and_Cliff_Randall.html?viewtab=News%20%26%20MP3s/ |title=Red Rhythm: Simon Britton, Cliff Randall and Dil Ajufo |publisher=[[Bucks Music Group]] |date=5 April 2008 |accessdate=30 July 2015 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> during his early years where he worked with [[Boyz II Men]], [[Electric Giant Beatz]] among others.  He is currently signed with Trakk Records.\n\n==Music==\n\n===Red Rhythm===\nDiL was part of Red Rhythm's producer, songwriter and [[remix]] team along with [[Simon Britton]] and Cliff Randal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cubesoundtracks.co.uk/composers/Red_Rhythm_Simon_Britton_and_Cliff_Randall.html?viewtab=Biog |title=Red Rhythm: Simon Britton and Cliff Randall \u2013 Bucks Music Group |publisher=Cubesoundtracks.co.uk |accessdate=9 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426091102/http://www.cubesoundtracks.co.uk/composers/Red_Rhythm_Simon_Britton_and_Cliff_Randall.html?viewtab=Biog |archive-date=26 April 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> whose credits include:\n[[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]], [[Aaliyah]], [[Boyz II Men]], [[Sean Paul]], [[Tara McDonald]], [[Run DMC]], [[Liberty X]], [[Kool & The Gang]], [[Aggro Santos]], [[Kimberly Wyatt]], [[Electric Giant Beatz]],<ref name=\"Michelle Williams featuring DiL\">{{cite web|author=Michelle Williams featuring DiL |url=http://djgarthy.blogspot.com/2011/08/electric-giant-beatz-feat-michelle.html |title=Electric Giant Beatz Feat Michelle Williams \u2013 On The Run |publisher=Dj Garthy |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref> [[Chaka Demus & Pliers]], [[Michelle Williams (singer)|Michelle Williams]]<ref name=\"Michelle Williams featuring DiL\"/> [[Missy Elliott]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Talib Kweli]], [[Timbaland]], [[Leona Lewis]].<ref name=\"Leona Lewis Featuring DiL\">{{cite web|author=Leona Lewis Featuring DiL |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Dip-Down-Rhythm-Remix-feat/dp/B00KLM7P78 |title=\nDip Down (Red Rhythm Remix) feat Dil|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref><br />\nDiL has shared the stage with many artists. He performed at the ''Corporate Elite Show 2014''<ref>{{cite web|author=Corporate Elite Show |url=http://laurelspot1.blogspot.com/2014/11/2014-corporate-elite-season-8.html |title=Corporate Elite Show 2014 |publisher=Laurelspot1 |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref> at the [[Eko Hotels and Suites]] in Nigeria alongside [[Iyanya]], [[Mavin Records]], [[Dru Hill]], [[Freddie Jackson]], [[Cameo (band)]] and many more.\n\n==Early life and career beginnings==\n\nDiL was born in London. He spent a few of his early years in [[Nigeria]] and moved back to London in the mid 1990s. He studied at [[Southwark College]] and later obtained a degree from [[West London University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mercury.tvu.ac.uk/~paulo/bitstream/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=665&Itemid=40 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215194800/http://mercury.tvu.ac.uk/~paulo/bitstream/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=665&Itemid=40 |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 February 2016 |title=University Project |publisher=University Of West London |accessdate=30 July 2015 }}</ref><br /> He first started producing on a [[PlayStation 2]] where he caught the attention of [[Simon Britton]]. He later teamed up with ''Red Rhythm'' and [[Simon Britton]] in 2004 as a producer and worked on various projects which included [[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]], [[Aaliyah]], [[Boyz II Men]], [[Sean Paul]], [[Tara McDonald]], [[Run DMC]], [[Liberty X]], [[Kool & The Gang]], [[Aggro Santos]], [[Kimberly Wyatt]], [[Electric Giant Beatz]],<ref name=\"Michelle Williams featuring DiL\"/> [[Chaka Demus & Pliers]], [[Michelle Williams (singer)|Michelle Williams]]<ref name=\"Michelle Williams featuring DiL\"/> [[Missy Elliott]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Talib Kweli]], [[Timbaland]], [[Leona Lewis]].<ref name=\"Leona Lewis Featuring DiL\"/> \nHe received a silver sales award for his work on [[LaVelle Smith Jnr]]'s ''Bodylicious Workout DVD''<br /> He later started working on remixes and cover songs with ''Red Rhythm'' under his company at the time ''Blaq Money''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Blaq Money |url=https://www.google.com/search?q=blaqmoney+red+rhythm&ie=utf-8&oe=utf-8 |title=Red Rhythm And Blaqmoney |publisher=Google |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref> DiL started his career as a solo artist in 2010 and in 2013, he released his first official single titled ''Acapella''<ref>{{cite web|author=Acapella Featuring Praiz and Lynxxx |url=http://tooxclusive.com/videodownload/dil-acapella-ft-praiz-lynxxx/ |title=VIDEO: DiL \u2013 Acapella f. Praiz & Lynxxx |publisher=too xclusive |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref> which featured ''Praiz'' and [[Lynxxx]]. He released his second official single ''Pretty Girls''<ref name=\"Pretty Girls\"/> in 2014 and this time featured afro pop star [[Iyanya]]. In early 2015 he collaborated with [[Yemi Alade]] on a song for her [[King of Queens (album)|King of Queens]]. The video for the song ''Temperature\"<ref name=\"Temperature\"/> which he featured on was released in March 2015\n\n===Other notable appearances===\n\n==Reality TV==\n\n===''Queer Eye for the Straight Guy''===\nIn 2004, DiL appeared alongside [[Simon Britton]] in the [[NBC]] America/[[Bravo (US TV channel)|Bravo TV]] show ''[[Queer Eye for the Straight Guy]]''<ref>{{cite web|author=DiL in Queer Eye for the Straight Guy |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CMQr1-CnnMA |title=DiL in Queer Eye for the Straight Guy |via=YouTube |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref> it was a popular reality television show in America at the time. It was also the first time the show had gone outside of the United States and they came to the UK for a one-off special. [[Simon Britton]], DiL and Cliff Randal ended the show with a one-off gig at the [[Scala (club)|Scala]] in London for a CD release launch party, featuring the single \"Someone Call The Doctor\".\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://trakkrecords.com/}}\n\n[[Category:British singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Mr DiL\n| background      = solo_singer\n| image           = DiL pic.jpg\n| caption         = DiL during a photoshoot\n| birth_name      = Dil Anthony Chike Ajufo\n| birth_place     = [[Westminster]], London, UK.\n| genre           = [[R&B]], Pop, [[Afro pop music|Afropop]], [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| occupation      = Musician<br />songwriter<br />[[sound engineer]]<br />producer\n| years_active    = 2005\u2013present\n| label           = Trakk Records<br />[[Red Rhythm]]\n| associated_acts = [[Iyanya]]<br />[[Yemi Alade]]<br />[[Lynxxx]]<br />[[Praiz]] \n| website         = {{URL|www.trakkrecords.com}}\n}}\n'''Dil Anthony Ajufo aka DiL or Mr DiL''' is a [[British Nigerian|British-Nigerian]] singer and producer.<ref>{{cite web|title=UK returnee, DIL on why he relocated to Nigeria|url=http://encomium.ng/uk-returnee-dil-on-why-he-relocated-to-nigeria/|publisher=Encomium|accessdate=12 August 2015|date=21 March 2014}}</ref> He is best known for his 2015 song \"Pretty Girls\"<ref name=\"Pretty Girls\">{{cite web |url = http://lindaikeji.blogspot.com/2014/12/new-video-dil-feat-iyanya-pretty-girls.html |title = New Video: DIL feat Iyanya \u2013 Pretty Girls |publisher = [[Linda Ikeji]] |date = 13 December 2014|accessdate = 30 July 2015 }}</ref> featuring [[Iyanya]]. He is also known for his collaboration with [[Yemi Alade]] on the popular song \"Temperature\".<ref name=\"Temperature\">{{cite web |url = http://www.bellanaija.com/2015/03/13/new-video-yemi-alade-featuring-dil-temperature/ |title = New Video: Yemi Alade featuring Dil \u2013 Temperature |publisher = [[BellaNaija]] |date = 13 March 2015|accessdate = 30 July 2015 }}</ref> On his debut single \"Acapella\" he collaborated with [[Lynxxx]] and Praiz. He was signed with Red Rhythm<ref name=\"Red Rhythm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bucksmusicgroup.com/composers/Red_Rhythm_Simon_Britton_and_Cliff_Randall.html?viewtab=News%20%26%20MP3s/ |title=Red Rhythm: Simon Britton, Cliff Randall and Dil Ajufo |publisher=[[Bucks Music Group]] |date=5 April 2008 |accessdate=30 July 2015 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> during his early years where he worked with [[Boyz II Men]], [[Electric Giant Beatz]] among others.  He is currently signed with Trakk Records.\n\n==Music==\n\n===Red Rhythm===\nDiL was part of Red Rhythm's producer, songwriter and [[remix]] team along with [[Simon Britton]] and Cliff Randal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cubesoundtracks.co.uk/composers/Red_Rhythm_Simon_Britton_and_Cliff_Randall.html?viewtab=Biog |title=Red Rhythm: Simon Britton and Cliff Randall \u2013 Bucks Music Group |publisher=Cubesoundtracks.co.uk |accessdate=9 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426091102/http://www.cubesoundtracks.co.uk/composers/Red_Rhythm_Simon_Britton_and_Cliff_Randall.html?viewtab=Biog |archive-date=26 April 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> whose credits include:\n[[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]], [[Aaliyah]], [[Boyz II Men]], [[Sean Paul]], [[Tara McDonald]], [[Run DMC]], [[Liberty X]], [[Kool & The Gang]], [[Aggro Santos]], [[Kimberly Wyatt]], [[Electric Giant Beatz]],<ref name=\"Michelle Williams featuring DiL\">{{cite web|author=Michelle Williams featuring DiL |url=http://djgarthy.blogspot.com/2011/08/electric-giant-beatz-feat-michelle.html |title=Electric Giant Beatz Feat Michelle Williams \u2013 On The Run |publisher=Dj Garthy |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref> [[Chaka Demus & Pliers]], [[Michelle Williams (singer)|Michelle Williams]]<ref name=\"Michelle Williams featuring DiL\"/> [[Missy Elliott]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Talib Kweli]], [[Timbaland]], [[Leona Lewis]].<ref name=\"Leona Lewis Featuring DiL\">{{cite web|author=Leona Lewis Featuring DiL |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Dip-Down-Rhythm-Remix-feat/dp/B00KLM7P78 |title=\nDip Down (Red Rhythm Remix) feat Dil|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref><br />\nDiL has shared the stage with many artists. He performed at the ''Corporate Elite Show 2014''<ref>{{cite web|author=Corporate Elite Show |url=http://laurelspot1.blogspot.com/2014/11/2014-corporate-elite-season-8.html |title=Corporate Elite Show 2014 |publisher=Laurelspot1 |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref> at the [[Eko Hotels and Suites]] in Nigeria alongside [[Iyanya]], [[Mavin Records]], [[Dru Hill]], [[Freddie Jackson]], [[Cameo (band)]] and many more.\n\n==Early life and career beginnings==\n\nDiL was born in London. He spent a few of his early years in [[Nigeria]] and moved back to London in the mid 90's. He studied at [[Southwark College]] and later obtained a degree from [[West London University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mercury.tvu.ac.uk/~paulo/bitstream/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=665&Itemid=40 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215194800/http://mercury.tvu.ac.uk/~paulo/bitstream/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=665&Itemid=40 |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 February 2016 |title=University Project |publisher=University Of West London |accessdate=30 July 2015 }}</ref><br /> He first started producing on a [[PlayStation 2]] where he caught the attention of [[Simon Britton]]. He later teamed up with ''Red Rhythm'' and [[Simon Britton]] in 2004 as a producer and worked on various projects which included [[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]], [[Aaliyah]], [[Boyz II Men]], [[Sean Paul]], [[Tara McDonald]], [[Run DMC]], [[Liberty X]], [[Kool & The Gang]], [[Aggro Santos]], [[Kimberly Wyatt]], [[Electric Giant Beatz]],<ref name=\"Michelle Williams featuring DiL\"/> [[Chaka Demus & Pliers]], [[Michelle Williams (singer)|Michelle Williams]]<ref name=\"Michelle Williams featuring DiL\"/> [[Missy Elliott]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Talib Kweli]], [[Timbaland]], [[Leona Lewis]].<ref name=\"Leona Lewis Featuring DiL\"/> \nHe received a silver sales award for his work on [[LaVelle Smith Jnr]]'s ''Bodylicious Workout DVD''<br /> He later started working on remixes and cover songs with ''Red Rhythm'' under his company at the time ''Blaq Money''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Blaq Money |url=https://www.google.com/search?q=blaqmoney+red+rhythm&ie=utf-8&oe=utf-8 |title=Red Rhythm And Blaqmoney |publisher=Google |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref> DiL started his career as a solo artist in 2010 and in 2013, he released his first official single titled ''Acapella''<ref>{{cite web|author=Acapella Featuring Praiz and Lynxxx |url=http://tooxclusive.com/videodownload/dil-acapella-ft-praiz-lynxxx/ |title=VIDEO: DiL \u2013 Acapella f. Praiz & Lynxxx |publisher=too xclusive |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref> which featured ''Praiz'' and [[Lynxxx]]. He released his second official single ''Pretty Girls''<ref name=\"Pretty Girls\"/> in 2014 and this time featured afro pop star [[Iyanya]]. In early 2015 he collaborated with [[Yemi Alade]] on a song for her [[King of Queens (album)|King of Queens]]. The video for the song ''Temperature\"<ref name=\"Temperature\"/> which he featured on was released in March 2015\n\n===Other notable appearances===\n\n==Reality TV==\n\n===''Queer Eye for the Straight Guy''===\nIn 2004, DiL appeared alongside [[Simon Britton]] in the [[NBC]] America/[[Bravo (US TV channel)|Bravo TV]] show ''[[Queer Eye for the Straight Guy]]''<ref>{{cite web|author=DiL in Queer Eye for the Straight Guy |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CMQr1-CnnMA |title=DiL in Queer Eye for the Straight Guy |via=YouTube |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref> it was a popular reality television show in America at the time. It was also the first time the show had gone outside of the United States and they came to the UK for a one-off special. [[Simon Britton]], DiL and Cliff Randal ended the show with a one-off gig at the [[Scala (club)|Scala]] in London for a CD release launch party, featuring the single \"Someone Call The Doctor\".\n\n