blisher=Waqt News TV|access-date=22 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220120253/http://waqtnews.tv/episode/the-right-24-february-2012|archive-date=20 February 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Right Question 10 March|url=http://waqtnews.tv/episode/the-right-question-10-march-2012|publisher=Waqt News|access-date=1 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127124955/http://waqtnews.tv/episode/the-right-question-10-march-2012|archive-date=27 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Waqt News 3 March|url=http://waqtnews.tv/episode/the-right-question-03-march-2012|publisher=Waqt News|access-date=1 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127130331/http://waqtnews.tv/episode/the-right-question-03-march-2012|archive-date=27 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>   He also appears as an analyst on ''AAJ Markets'' (AAJ TV), ''Morning Shout'' (Business Plus), and ''Daily Business'' (INN-Indus News).\nNasir also narrated and hosted a documentary on [[Quaid-e-Azam]], the founder of Pakistan (in English). \nNasir has been awarded the best anchor in the business category on 22 February (7th Consumer Choice Awards).<ref>{{Citation|last = Ali Nasir|title = Ali Nasir receiving 7th Consumers Choice Award 2011|date = 2012-03-29|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ch9V8kOix0k|accessdate = 2016-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nasir, Ali}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani economists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani television hosts]]\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:People from Sialkot]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ali_Nasir"}
{"title_page": "Kris M. Balderston", "text_new": "{{no footnotes|date=August 2014}}\n[[File:Kris Balderston, Global Impact Economy Forum, April 26, 2012 crop.jpg|thumb|upright|Kris Balderston delivering remarks at the Global Impact Economy Forum, 2012]]\n[http://fleishmanhillard.com/2013/02/07/state-department-official-kris-balderston-to-lead-fleishman-hillards-washington-d-c-office/ Kris M. Balderston] is General Manager of the Fleishman-Hillard Washington, DC office.  His 25-year career in Washington includes leadership positions across the U.S. Government, from the White House, U.S. Senate, and State Department.\n\nPreviously, he served as the Secretary's Special Representative for Global Partnerships and managed the [[Secretary of State's Office of Global Partnerships|Global Partnership Initiative]] in the [[United States Secretary of State|Office of the Secretary of State]]. Prior to his role at the [[United States Department of State]], Balderston was [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Hillary Clinton]]'s first [[legislative director]] in January 2001, before serving as her Deputy Chief of Staff from 2002 to 2009.\n\nBalderston began his career with the [[National Governors' Association]] and then ran the Massachusetts State Office for [[Governor of Massachusetts|Governor]] [[Michael Dukakis]] from 1987\u20131991. He became Senior Policy Advisor to [[Party leaders of the United States Senate|Senate Majority Leader]] [[George J. Mitchell|George Mitchell]] at the [[Democratic Policy Committee Chairman of the United States Senate|Senate Democratic Policy Committee]] from 1991 to 1993. From 1993 to 1995, he served as the Deputy Chief of Staff at the [[United States Department of Labor|Department of Labor]] under [[United States Secretary of Labor|Secretary of Labor]] [[Robert Reich]]. Kris served in the [[White House]] under [[Bill Clinton]] from 1995 to 2001, as [[Special Assistant to the President]] for Cabinet Affairs and then later as the [[Deputy Assistant to the President]] and the Deputy Secretary to the Cabinet.\n\nBalderston holds his [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[political science]] from [[Le Moyne College]] and his [[Master of Arts]] in [[government]] from [[Georgetown University]].\n\n==External links==\n*The Great Convener [http://www.thecro.com/content/great-convener]\n*Interview with Forbes India [http://forbesindia.com/article/special/kris-m-balderston-we-want-people-to-know-that-what-theyre-going-to-buy-is-going-be-good/33314/1]\n*Creating Value through Uncommon Alliances [http://www.ssireview.org/articles/entry/creating_value_through_uncommon_alliances]\n*Accelerating the Impact Economy Through Investment and Innovation [http://www.ssireview.org/blog/entry/at_the_state_dept._contributing_to_an_impact_economy]\n*Investing with Impact: Unlocking Value for Business and Society [http://www.mitpressjournals.org/doi/abs/10.1162/INOV_a_00080?journalCode=itgg]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Balderston, Kris M.}}\n[[Category:American diplomats]]\n[[Category:Le Moyne College alumni]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:United States Special Envoys]]\n[[Category:The Stimson Center]]\n", "text_old": "{{no footnotes|date=August 2014}}\n[[File:Kris Balderston, Global Impact Economy Forum, April 26, 2012 crop.jpg|thumb|upright|Kris Balderston delivering remarks at the Global Impact Economy Forum, 2012]]\n[http://fleishmanhillard.com/2013/02/07/state-department-official-kris-balderston-to-lead-fleishman-hillards-washington-d-c-office/ Kris M. Balderston] is General Manager of the Fleishman-Hillard Washington, DC office.  His 25-year career in Washington includes leadership positions across the U.S. Government, from the White House, U.S. Senate, and State Department.\n\nPreviously, he served as the Secretary's Special Representative for Global Partnerships and managed the [[Secretary of State's Office of Global Partnerships|Global Partnership Initiative]] in the [[United States Secretary of State|Office of the Secretary of State]]. Prior to his role at the [[United States Department of State]], Balderston was [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Hillary Clinton]]'s first [[legislative director]] in January 2001, before serving as her Deputy Chief of Staff from 2002 to 2009.\n\nBalderston began his career with the [[National Governors' Association]] and then ran the Massachusetts State Office for [[Governor of Massachusetts|Governor]] [[Michael Dukakis]] from 1987-1991. He became Senior Policy Advisor to [[Party leaders of the United States Senate|Senate Majority Leader]] [[George J. Mitchell|George Mitchell]] at the [[Democratic Policy Committee Chairman of the United States Senate|Senate Democratic Policy Committee]] from 1991 to 1993. From 1993 to 1995, he served as the Deputy Chief of Staff at the [[United States Department of Labor|Department of Labor]] under [[United States Secretary of Labor|Secretary of Labor]] [[Robert Reich]]. Kris served in the [[White House]] under [[Bill Clinton]] from 1995 to 2001, as [[Special Assistant to the President]] for Cabinet Affairs and then later as the [[Deputy Assistant to the President]] and the Deputy Secretary to the Cabinet.\n\nBalderston holds his [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[political science]] from [[Le Moyne College]] and his [[Master of Arts]] in [[government]] from [[Georgetown University]].\n\n==External links==\n*The Great Convener [http://www.thecro.com/content/great-convener]\n*Interview with Forbes India [http://forbesindia.com/article/special/kris-m-balderston-we-want-people-to-know-that-what-theyre-going-to-buy-is-going-be-good/33314/1]\n*Creating Value through Uncommon Alliances [http://www.ssireview.org/articles/entry/creating_value_through_uncommon_alliances]\n*Accelerating the Impact Economy Through Investment and Innovation [http://www.ssireview.org/blog/entry/at_the_state_dept._contributing_to_an_impact_economy]\n*Investing with Impact: Unlocking Value for Business and Society [http://www.mitpressjournals.org/doi/abs/10.1162/INOV_a_00080?journalCode=itgg]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Balderston, Kris M.}}\n[[Category:American diplomats]]\n[[Category:Le Moyne College alumni]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:United States Special Envoys]]\n[[Category:The Stimson Center]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1987-1991 \u2192 1987\u20131991", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kris_M._Balderston"}
{"title_page": "Tina Takahashi", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian judoka}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| birth_place = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n| residence = [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]]\n| website = http://www.tinatak.com/\n| country = [[Canada]]\n| sport = [[Judo]]\n| rank = {{JudoRank|red|white}} ''Rokudan'' (6th dan)\n| club = Takahashi Dojo\n| updated = 3 September 2012\n}}\n\n'''Tina Takahashi''' is a [[judoka]], coach, and author who won [[Canada|Canada's]] first ever gold medal in international [[Judo]] at the [[World University Games]] in 1984, and was Canada's first women's [[Judo at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Judo]] coach in 1988, coaching Canada's first women's Judo Olympian [[Sandra Greaves]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Canada wins 1st gold in a world judo event|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=IqIkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=sqUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5013%2C6486265|accessdate=18 August 2012|newspaper=The Montreal Gazette|date=10 December 1984}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Local Judo Athlete Plays On|url=http://newswest.org/easyread/archives/250|accessdate=18 August 2012|newspaper=Newswest Online|date=21 October 2010}}</ref> She was the first Canadian woman to achieve the rank of ''roku-dan'' (sixth-degree black belt), and the first women's [[Sport Canada]] carded athlete. Takahashi was Canadian champion 9 times, has taught Judo for more than 30 years, and was inducted into the Judo Canada Hall of Fame in 1998.  Also in 2016 she was inducted into the Ottawa sports hall of fame.<ref>{{cite book|last=Takahashi|first=Masao|title=Mastering Judo|year=2005|publisher=Human Kinetics|location=Windsor, Ontario|isbn=073605099X|author2=Family |pages=214}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hall of Fame|url=http://www.judoontario.ca/awards_recognition/hall_of_fame|work=Judo Ontario website|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref> In 2008, she was named as Chair of the National Grading Board by Judo Canada.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tina Takahashi named as Chair of the NGB|url=http://www.judoontario.ca/news/view/40|work=Judo Ontario website|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref> Takahashi is the daughter of Canadian judoka [[Masao Takahashi]] and [[June Takahashi]], and the sister of Olympians [[Phil Takahashi]] and [[Ray Takahashi]].\n\nIn 2005, she co-authored a book titled ''Mastering Judo'' with her parents and three siblings.<ref>{{cite book|last=Takahashi|first=Masao|title=Mastering Judo|year=2005|publisher=Human Kinetics|location=Windsor, Ontario|isbn=073605099X|author2=Family }}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* {{cite book|last=Takahashi|first=Masao|title=Mastering Judo|year=2005|publisher=Human Kinetics|location=Windsor, Ontario|isbn=073605099X|author2=Family }}\n\n== Education ==\nBachelor of Physical Education, Bachelor of Education & Ontario Teachers Certificate\n\n== Championships and Accomplishments ==\n\n=== Highlights ===\n* Judo Canada Hall of Fame Inductee\n* Former Olympic judo coach\n* World University Judo champion\n* 6th degree black belt\n* Former World [[Sambo (martial art)|Sambo]] Champion\n* Co-Author of \"Mastering Judo\" by Masao Takahashi & Family\n\n=== Competitive Highlights (National and International Tournaments) ===\n* World University Championship 1st place: 1984 France\n* World Sambo Championships 1stplace: 1980 Montreal\n* Pacific Rim: 1st twice: 1981 Japan, 1980 Hawaii\n* World Championships5th twice:  1980 USA, & 1982 France\n* Senior Canadian Judo Nationals 1st eight times: 1976, \u201978, \u201979, \u201880, \u201881, \u201882, \u201883, \u201884\n* Canada Cup 1st:1980 Montreal\n* Cadet Canadian Nationals1st three times: 1974, \u201976, \u201977\n* Medaled at over15 international tournaments in Europe, North and South America, & Japan including:\n* Quebec Open 1stthree times: 1979, 80, 81 Montreal\n* Pan Am Games 3rd:1983 Caracas, Venezuela\n* French International 3rd: 1981 France\n* British Open3rd: 1977 England\n* Dutch Open 3rd: 1981 Holland\n* Pan American Championships, 3rd three times: 1982 Chile, \u201984 Mexico, \u201985 Cuba\n* Pan American Championships 2nd:1980 Venezuela\n* Desert Open 1st:1980 Arizona\n\n=== Awards ===\n* Ottawa Sport Hall of Fame - (inducted June 3, 2016)\n* Canadian Asian of the Year finalist, Sheila Copps Award - 2011\n* Female Coach of the Year Award Judo Ontario - 2010\n* Life member Judo Ontario/Judo Canada\n* Certificate of Recognition, Pioneer of Women's Competitive Judo JC - 2006\n* Judo Ontario Hall of Fame - 2002\n* Inducted into:  Judo Canada Hall of Fame - 1998\n* City of Nepean Wall of Fame - 1986\n* Canadian Sport Award, Athlete of the Month - 1984\n* Int\u2019l Achievement Award, Sport Federation of Canada - 1980\n* Ontario Distinguished Performance Achievement Award - \u201976-\u201884\n\n=== Judo Canada CAREER ACHIEVEMENT CATEGORIES ===\n* COACHING: \u201988 OLYMPICS, \u201986 WORLDS, \u201987 WORLDS COMPETITOR: \u201980 WORLDS, \u201982 WORLDS, \u201984 WORLDS CONTRIBUTION TO SPORT: Chair National Grading Board ORIGINAL SENSEI: RENEE HOCK \u201993 & \u201995 WORLDS Promoted to Rokudan (6th degree) in 2003 (14 years as 6th dan)  Judo practitioner for over 50 years, teaching/coaching for 40 years.\n** Coached Women\u2019s National team at over 20 international tournaments throughout Europe, Asia, Africa, North, South and Central America\n** Participated in many national and international training camps and clinics throughout the world. NCCP level 3 certified\n** Judo Ontario Provincial Coach at several National Championships\n** Coached Ontario Winter Games for the East Region\n** Coached Women\u2019s National Team in Ottawa \u201885-\u201888, and at the Seoul Olympics. Judo Canada National Team Resource Coach until mid 1990s. Tina's three sons who are all National judo medalists.  (Adam 3rd 2015 2nd 2011), Torin (1st x 2, 2011, 2012, 2nd x2, 2015, 2013, 2009 +), Liam Macfadyen (3rd 2012)\n** Taught judo to children, teens and adults recreationally and in schools for 40 years.\n** Taught judo to '''Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]]''' and his brothers and all the children of former '''Prime Minister, [[Brian Mulroney]]'''\n\n=== Coaching Highlights with Women\u2019s National Team ===\n* Olympic Games 1988 in Korea\n* World Championships 1986 in Netherlands\n* World Championships 1987 in Germany\n* Pan Am Games in 1987 in Indianapolis, USA\n* Francophonie Games in 1989 in Morocco\n* Fukuoka Int\u2019l Women\u2019s Championships 3 times in Japan\n\n=== Volunteer Highlights ===\n* Chairperson for Judo Canada\u2019s National Grading Board 2008\n* Member of Judo Canada National Grading Board 2004-2008\n* Member Judo Ontario Black Belt Grading Board 2000-present\n* Women\u2019s National Judo Team Representative mid \u201880s\n* Assistant Regional Director of East Region early \u201890s\n* Provincial \"A\" referee\n* East Region Tournament Organizer\n\n=== Kata (Pre-arranged forms/patterns of movement) ===\n* 1st place inNage no Kata CNE Int\u2019l 1989, medaled in Ju-no- kata, Katame-no-kata\n* Course conductor kata, gokyo and competitive clinics in Ontario and Quebec\n* Judge Pan Ams and several Nationals\n* Chair for the National Grading Board\n* Organizer of kata judging seminars in 2008 with Kuniko Takeuchi Sensei, Chairperson Pan Am Kata Committee\n\n=== Athlete Development (National and International Judo Champions) ===\nOriginal sensei, coached many athletes from children to national and international champions.  i.e.  Renee Hock (World competitor \u201993, \u201995, many int\u2019l medals, Sr.Ntl champ \u201886), Tony Walby (para Olympics 2012, IBSA Worlds 2014, Sr. Ntl Champ 2008 & multi time National medals), Evan O\u2019Leary (Masters Ntl champ), Karen Hayde (KDK Cup Brazil champ, Sr. Ntl champ \u201895), Linda Konkol (Sr. Ntl champ \u201889), Julie Leblanc (Sr. Ntl champ \u201985, US Open 2nd, 3rd, \u2018\u201987-\u201988)  Michael and Kristina Kiss (Juv. Ntl champs) Dave Shapiro (Juv, Ntl champ), Torin Macfadyen (U18 Ntl champ, U15 Ntl Champ), Sean Macfadyen (Masters Pan Am champ \u201907, QC Open \u201909, RMC Int\u2019l 2009, Sr. Prov Team member) Stewart Tanaka (Sr. Ntl medalist), Thomas Filter (Jr. Ntl champ '02), Alicia Rimad (U17 Ntl Champ '10)\n\n==Videos and Photos==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9VfneKWyA60 Tina Takahashi on CTV Ottawa Morning Live, Part 1], [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UznwaceV_Bs Part 2], [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l_wDY0OeedQ Part 3] (CTV Ottawa Morning Live on YouTube)\n* [http://www.tinatak.com/about/videos.html Tina Takahashi Martial Art and Fitness] (Videos)\n* [http://www.tinatak.com/about/photos.html#!Tina___Portrait Photos]\n\n== Tina Takahashi Martial Arts and Fitness ==\nTina Takahashi Martial Arts and Fitness offers courses in [http://www.tinatak.com/adults/judo-ottawa.html Judo], [http://www.tinatak.com/adults/sport-sambo.html Sambo], [http://www.tinatak.com/adults/karate-ottawa.html Karate], [http://www.tinatak.com/adults/kun-khmer-muay-thai-kickboxing.html Khun Khmer (Cambodian-Kick Boxing -Muay Thai boxing)], [http://www.tinatak.com/adults/wrestling.html Wrestling], [http://www.tinatak.com/adults/brazilian-jiu-jitsu-ottawa.html Brazilian Jiu-jitsu] and traditional [http://www.tinatak.com/adults/jujutsu.html Ju-jutsu]. With decades of experience under their belt, the school is operated by Tina Takahashi and her spouse, Sean MacFadyen.\n* [http://www.tinatak.com/adults.html Adult Classes]\n* [http://www.tinatak.com/adults/womens-classes.html Women's Classes]\n* [http://www.tinatak.com/kids.html Kids Classes]\n* [http://www.tinatak.com/schedule.html Schedule]\n* [http://www.tinatak.com/about/instructors.html Instructors]\n* [http://www.tinatak.com/about/reviews.html Reviews]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Judo in Canada]]\n* [[List of Canadian judoka]]\n* [http://www.tinatak.com/about/press.html Press]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{JudoInside|21357<!-- /tina_takahashi -->}}\n* [http://www.tinatak.com/ Tina Takahashi Martial Arts]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Takahashi, Tina}}\n[[Category:Canadian female judoka]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Canadian sportspeople of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in judo]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games bronze medalists for Canada]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Ottawa]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Judoka at the 1983 Pan American Games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian judoka}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| birth_place = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n| residence = [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]]\n| website = http://www.tinatak.com/\n| country = [[Canada]]\n| sport = [[Judo]]\n| rank = {{JudoRank|red|white}} ''Rokudan'' (6th dan)\n| club = Takahashi Dojo\n| updated = 3 September 2012\n}}\n\n'''Tina Takahashi''' is a [[judoka]], coach, and author who won [[Canada|Canada's]] first ever gold medal in international [[Judo]] at the [[World University Games]] in 1984, and was Canada's first women's [[Judo at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Judo]] coach in 1988, coaching Canada's first women's Judo Olympian [[Sandra Greaves]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Canada wins 1st gold in a world judo event|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=IqIkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=sqUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5013%2C6486265|accessdate=18 August 2012|newspaper=The Montreal Gazette|date=10 December 1984}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Local Judo Athlete Plays On|url=http://newswest.org/easyread/archives/250|accessdate=18 August 2012|newspaper=Newswest Online|date=21 October 2010}}</ref> She was the first Canadian woman to achieve the rank of ''roku-dan'' (sixth-degree black belt), and the first women's [[Sport Canada]] carded athlete. Takahashi was Canadian champion 9 times, has taught Judo for more than 30 years, and was inducted into the Judo Canada Hall of Fame in 1998.  Also in 2016 she was inducted into the Ottawa sports hall of fame.<ref>{{cite book|last=Takahashi|first=Masao|title=Mastering Judo|year=2005|publisher=Human Kinetics|location=Windsor, Ontario|isbn=073605099X|author2=Family |pages=214}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hall of Fame|url=http://www.judoontario.ca/awards_recognition/hall_of_fame|work=Judo Ontario website|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref> In 2008, she was named as Chair of the National Grading Board by Judo Canada.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tina Takahashi named as Chair of the NGB|url=http://www.judoontario.ca/news/view/40|work=Judo Ontario website|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref> Takahashi is the daughter of Canadian judoka [[Masao Takahashi]] and [[June Takahashi]], and the sister of Olympians [[Phil Takahashi]] and [[Ray Takahashi]].\n\nIn 2005, she co-authored a book titled ''Mastering Judo'' with her parents and three siblings.<ref>{{cite book|last=Takahashi|first=Masao|title=Mastering Judo|year=2005|publisher=Human Kinetics|location=Windsor, Ontario|isbn=073605099X|author2=Family }}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* {{cite book|last=Takahashi|first=Masao|title=Mastering Judo|year=2005|publisher=Human Kinetics|location=Windsor, Ontario|isbn=073605099X|author2=Family }}\n\n== Education ==\nBachelor of Physical Education, Bachelor of Education & Ontario Teachers Certificate\n\n== Championships and Accomplishments ==\n\n=== Highlights ===\n* Judo Canada Hall of Fame Inductee\n* Former Olympic judo coach\n* World University Judo champion\n* 6th degree black belt\n* Former World [[Sambo (martial art)|Sambo]] Champion\n* Co-Author of \"Mastering Judo\" by Masao Takahashi & Family\n\n=== Competitive Highlights (National and International Tournaments) ===\n* World University Championship 1st place: 1984 France\n* World Sambo Championships 1stplace: 1980 Montreal\n* Pacific Rim: 1st twice: 1981 Japan, 1980 Hawaii\n* World Championships5th twice:  1980 USA, & 1982 France\n* Senior Canadian Judo Nationals 1st eight times: 1976, \u201978, \u201979, \u201880, \u201881, \u201882, \u201883, \u201884\n* Canada Cup 1st:1980 Montreal\n* Cadet Canadian Nationals1st three times: 1974, \u201976, \u201977\n* Medaled at over15 internationa